        'Peer connection and professional community serve as critical buffers against both burnout and compassion fatigue. Regular consultation groups, peer supervision, and informal collegial support provide emotional processing outlets that individual coping strategies cannot replicate. Research on burnout prevention by Morse and colleagues found that interventions combining organizational changes with individual support were significantly more effective than either alone. The relational nature of therapy work means that relational support is uniquely well-suited to sustaining it.',
        'Finally, reconnecting with purpose is not a platitude — it is a research-supported burnout intervention. Studies on meaning-making and professional identity show that therapists who maintain a clear connection between their daily work and their broader values report lower burnout even when their objective workload is high. Regular reflection on what drew you to this work, what impact you are having, and what moments of genuine connection occurred in your recent sessions can counteract the emotional flatness that characterizes burnout.',
