        'Addressing therapist burnout requires a multi-level approach that combines individual practices, structural changes, and thoughtful technology adoption. At the individual level, the evidence supports regular self-monitoring of burnout symptoms using validated tools like the Maslach Burnout Inventory or the Professional Quality of Life Scale (ProQOL). Just as therapists use outcome measures to track client progress, monitoring their own well-being creates an early warning system that enables intervention before burnout becomes severe.',
        'At the structural level, examine your practice through Maslach\'s six domains: workload, control, reward, community, fairness, and values. Identify which domains are misaligned and develop specific, actionable plans to address them. If workload is the primary issue, the solution may involve reducing caseload, raising fees, or dropping insurance panels that create excessive administrative burden. If community is lacking, the solution may involve joining a consultation group or scheduling regular peer lunches. The key is specificity — vague self-care advice is less effective than targeted structural changes.',
        'Technology adoption should be strategic and selective. Audit the tools you currently use and honestly assess whether each one reduces or adds to your total workload. Consolidate where possible — a single platform that handles scheduling, documentation, and outcome tracking creates less friction than three separate systems. When evaluating new tools, prioritize those that automate tasks you currently perform manually rather than those that add new capabilities you did not previously have. The goal is subtraction, not addition.',
